2639ab2b-e3f8-4cba-a6dd-93e8f9617894	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	How many principles of Green Chemistry were proposed by Anastas and Warner?	6	10	12	15	C	Anastas and Warner proposed 12 Principles of Green Chemistry (1998). Key principles include: prevention of waste, atom economy, less hazardous synthesis, designing safer chemicals, use of renewable feedstocks, catalysis, and designing for degradation.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
fb2ad162-dea8-4ed2-9757-d9042841312b	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	Atom economy is defined as:	(Mass of desired product / Mass of all reactants) x 100	(Moles of product / Moles of reactant) x 100	Mass of waste / Mass of product	Number of atoms in product / Number of atoms in reactants	A	Atom economy = (Molecular weight of desired product / Sum of molecular weights of all reactants) x 100. High atom economy = fewer atoms wasted. Addition reactions have 100% atom economy. Substitution/elimination reactions have lower atom economy. Introduced by Barry Trost.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
fe40147d-84b3-43c6-9622-c3fc9376fac8	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	Which of the following solvents is considered "green"?	Benzene	Chloroform	Water	Carbon tetrachloride	C	Water is the greenest solvent — non-toxic, non-flammable, abundant, and cheap. Benzene, chloroform, and CCl4 are toxic and carcinogenic. Other green solvents include supercritical CO2, ionic liquids, and bio-based solvents like ethanol and ethyl lactate.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
91876379-66e5-4f12-820c-9cf6a6ff4c5a	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	The E-factor in green chemistry represents:	Energy consumed per mole of product	Mass of waste generated per mass of product	Efficiency of catalyst	Environmental toxicity index	B	E-factor (Environmental factor) = kg of waste per kg of desired product. Lower E-factor = greener process. Bulk chemicals: E-factor ~1-5. Pharmaceuticals: E-factor ~25-100. Introduced by Roger Sheldon. Used alongside atom economy to assess greenness of a process.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
f3506cba-ea0b-4347-91c4-7dd36bbd3c78	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	Which of the following is a renewable feedstock for green chemistry?	Petroleum	Natural gas	Biomass	Coal	C	Biomass (plant material, agricultural waste) is a renewable feedstock. Petroleum, natural gas, and coal are fossil fuels — non-renewable. Green chemistry principle 7: use renewable feedstocks. Bio-based chemicals from biomass reduce dependence on fossil fuels and lower carbon footprint.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
e904d48f-d17b-4e1e-b097-52ebd258021f	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	Nanotechnology deals with materials in the size range of:	1-10 mm	1-100 nm	1-100 micrometers	1-10 cm	B	Nanotechnology involves manipulation of matter at 1-100 nanometer (nm) scale. 1 nm = 10^-9 m. At this scale, materials exhibit unique optical, electrical, magnetic, and chemical properties different from bulk. Named by Norio Taniguchi (1974). Feynman's "There's Plenty of Room at the Bottom" (1959) inspired the field.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
c4caaba3-5c25-46d3-86e7-b462e7853925	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	Which of the following is a 0-dimensional nanomaterial?	Carbon nanotube	Graphene	Quantum dot	Nanofilm	C	Quantum dots are 0-dimensional (0D) nanomaterials — nanoscale in all 3 dimensions. Carbon nanotubes are 1D (nanoscale in 2 dimensions, long in 1). Graphene is 2D (nanoscale in 1 dimension — thickness). Bulk nanostructured materials are 3D. Dimensionality affects electronic and optical properties.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
