575ed925-baed-4210-ba50-19d18f5980ac	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	Silver nanoparticles are widely used for their:	Magnetic properties	Antimicrobial properties	Fluorescent properties	Semiconducting properties	B	Silver nanoparticles (AgNPs) have potent antimicrobial activity against bacteria, fungi, and viruses. They release Ag+ ions which disrupt microbial cell membranes and inhibit enzymes. Used in wound dressings, medical devices, water purification filters, and antimicrobial textiles.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
ecaea48b-2692-412e-84b3-2b0938f01213	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	Graphene is:	A 3D allotrope of carbon	A single layer of carbon atoms in hexagonal arrangement	A form of amorphous carbon	A carbon nanotube unrolled into sheets	B	Graphene is a single atomic layer of carbon atoms arranged in a 2D hexagonal lattice. It is the thinnest material known (1 atom thick), extremely strong, highly conductive (electrical and thermal), and transparent. Isolated by Geim and Novoselov (2010 Nobel Prize) using scotch tape method.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
85c5f294-511f-44a4-bdd0-de063f72fb4f	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	The use of catalysts in green chemistry is important because:	Catalysts increase the amount of waste produced	Catalysts allow reactions at milder conditions with less waste	Catalysts always require high temperature	Catalysts are always toxic	B	Principle 9 of Green Chemistry: Catalytic reagents are superior to stoichiometric reagents. Catalysts allow reactions at milder conditions (lower T, P), improve selectivity (less byproducts), and are not consumed. Examples: enzyme catalysis, heterogeneous catalysis, organocatalysis.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
aba4dc09-efac-4a97-9ea9-239c8d70725f	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	Quantum dots are nanoparticles that exhibit:	Fixed emission wavelength regardless of size	Size-dependent fluorescence emission	No optical properties	Only magnetic properties	B	Quantum dots (semiconductor nanocrystals, e.g., CdSe) show size-dependent fluorescence — smaller QDs emit blue light, larger QDs emit red light. This is due to quantum confinement effect. Used in LED displays, bioimaging, solar cells, and medical diagnostics.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
7acd2f58-b5df-4589-b9c5-c9d33d9a8472	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	Which of the following reactions has 100% atom economy?	Substitution reaction	Elimination reaction	Addition reaction	Decomposition reaction	C	Addition reactions incorporate ALL atoms of all reactants into the product — no atoms are wasted → 100% atom economy. Example: A + B → AB. Substitution reactions produce a leaving group (waste). Elimination produces small molecules (H2O, HX). Decomposition produces multiple products.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
648b17c0-3fab-4e48-8919-ba872b906bdb	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	The term "nano" comes from the Greek word meaning:	Small	Dwarf	Atom	Tiny	B	The prefix "nano" derives from the Greek word "nanos" meaning dwarf. 1 nanometer = 10^-9 meters = 0.000000001 m. For comparison: a human hair is ~80,000 nm wide, a DNA double helix is ~2 nm wide, and a hydrogen atom is ~0.1 nm.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
20bf3c9a-0b91-4ec5-8d66-024287d8c260	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	Biodiesel is an example of green chemistry because:	It is made from petroleum	It uses renewable biomass feedstock and is biodegradable	It produces more CO2 than diesel	It requires toxic catalysts	B	Biodiesel is produced from vegetable oils or animal fats (renewable) by transesterification with methanol. It is biodegradable, non-toxic, produces lower net CO2 (carbon neutral), and reduces particulate emissions. Demonstrates green principles: renewable feedstocks + reduced environmental impact.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
00a9d035-c789-415c-9033-c90b612006d9	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	Which allotrope of carbon is used in nanotechnology as a lubricant and conductor?	Diamond	Graphite	Fullerene C60	Amorphous carbon	C	Fullerene C60 (and its derivatives) are used in nanotechnology as lubricants (ball-bearing effect), organic solar cells, drug delivery vehicles, and superconductors (when doped with alkali metals). Carbon nanotubes are used as conductors. Graphite is used as a conventional lubricant.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
bde639ae-c424-4bb0-b5a4-069cea86fbde	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	The process of making nanoparticles from bulk material by breaking it down is called:	Bottom-up approach	Top-down approach	Self-assembly	Chemical vapor deposition	B	Top-down approach: bulk material broken down into nanoparticles (e.g., ball milling, lithography, laser ablation). Bottom-up approach: atoms/molecules assembled into nanostructures (e.g., chemical synthesis, CVD, self-assembly). Top-down is simpler but gives less control over size/shape.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
b1089f08-5421-4918-a699-4590424b9f5a	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	Which of the following is an ionic liquid?	NaCl dissolved in water	[BMIM][PF6] (1-butyl-3-methylimidazolium hexafluorophosphate)	Liquid ammonia	Molten iron	B	Ionic liquids are salts that are liquid at or near room temperature (< 100 deg C). [BMIM][PF6] is a classic example. They have negligible vapor pressure (non-volatile), wide liquid range, and tunable properties. Used as green solvents in catalysis and extraction as alternatives to volatile organic solvents.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
72aeaa8a-89a1-4434-9f2c-9273907bae4e	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	The scanning tunneling microscope (STM) was invented by:	Richard Feynman	Gerd Binnig and Heinrich Rohrer	Sumio Iijima	Eric Drexler	B	Scanning Tunneling Microscope (STM) was invented by Gerd Binnig and Heinrich Rohrer at IBM Zurich in 1981 (Nobel Prize 1986). STM images surfaces at atomic resolution using quantum tunneling current. It can also manipulate individual atoms — first demonstrated by moving xenon atoms to spell "IBM" (1989).	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
315bf105-c734-440c-825b-65033f2a937b	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	Gold nanoparticles appear red or purple in solution because of:	Chemical reaction with water	Surface plasmon resonance	Radioactive decay	Magnetic properties	B	Gold nanoparticles (AuNPs) appear red/purple due to surface plasmon resonance (SPR) — collective oscillation of conduction electrons at the nanoparticle surface absorbs visible light (~520 nm). Bulk gold appears yellow. Size and shape of AuNPs tune the SPR and hence color. Used in diagnostics (pregnancy tests) and photothermal therapy.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
ef059cda-45c2-4ee4-8afd-e4ccd6bd7c3c	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	In green chemistry, "designing for degradation" means:	Making polymers that never degrade	Designing products to break down into innocuous substances after use	Using degradation to generate energy	Avoiding all chemical reactions	B	Principle 10 of Green Chemistry: Chemical products should be designed so that at the end of their function they break down into innocuous degradation products and do not persist in the environment. Example: biodegradable plastics (PLA, PHBV) vs persistent conventional plastics.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
85fa69c1-a438-4d4c-b12c-45cf09a9eab0	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	Which of the following is NOT a property of carbon nanotubes?	High tensile strength	Electrical conductivity	Thermal conductivity	Solubility in water	D	Carbon nanotubes are insoluble in water (hydrophobic surface). They have exceptional tensile strength (~100x steel), high electrical conductivity (metallic SWCNTs), and high thermal conductivity (~3500 W/mK). Functionalization with -COOH or -OH groups can improve dispersibility in water.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
69d3beda-2f28-4f1b-8400-82b32b3d58d4	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	The use of microwave irradiation in organic synthesis is considered green because:	It uses more energy than conventional heating	It gives faster reactions with less solvent and energy	It generates more byproducts	It requires hazardous solvents	B	Microwave-assisted synthesis is green: reactions complete in minutes vs hours (energy efficient), often need less or no solvent, give better yields and selectivity. Microwave energy directly heats reaction mixture (no heat transfer losses). Reduces energy consumption and waste generation significantly.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
8e80ad68-6fa5-4539-8747-4c24f5cff143	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	Nanoparticles used in sunscreens (TiO2, ZnO) work by:	Absorbing and scattering UV radiation	Reacting chemically with UV	Producing vitamin D	Blocking only visible light	A	TiO2 and ZnO nanoparticles in sunscreens physically absorb and scatter UV radiation (both UVA and UVB). Nanoparticle size makes them transparent to visible light (no white cast) unlike bulk particles. They are photostable and broad-spectrum. Concerns exist about potential toxicity of nanoparticles penetrating skin.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
0d2dd6ae-5841-4e95-aada-71a161b403c3	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	Which of the following best describes a "green" synthesis?	High yield using excess toxic reagents	Efficient synthesis using non-toxic reagents with minimal waste	Any synthesis done in a laboratory	Synthesis that uses only inorganic reagents	B	A green synthesis maximizes atom economy, uses non-toxic/renewable reagents, minimizes or eliminates waste, uses safer solvents, and operates under mild conditions. The goal is to design processes that are safe, efficient, and environmentally benign from the outset, not to treat environmental problems after they occur.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
61e3e722-7f7b-4c56-930d-09f2d560f534	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	The bottom-up approach in nanotechnology involves:	Grinding bulk materials into nanoparticles	Building nanostructures atom by atom or molecule by molecule	Using lasers to cut bulk material	Lithographic etching of surfaces	B	Bottom-up approach builds nanostructures from atomic/molecular scale up — like atoms assembling into larger structures. Examples: chemical synthesis of nanoparticles, self-assembly, molecular beam epitaxy, CVD. Analogous to how nature builds (proteins fold, DNA assembles). Gives better size/shape control than top-down.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
b5fc265c-2127-4dac-a53b-28c1696af273	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	Which gas is used in supercritical fluid chromatography as a green alternative?	Nitrogen	CO2	Argon	Helium	B	Supercritical CO2 (scCO2) is used in supercritical fluid chromatography (SFC) as a green mobile phase alternative to organic solvents. It has low viscosity, high diffusivity, and is non-toxic. Used in food industry (extraction), pharmaceuticals (chiral separations), and environmental analysis.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
3033cfb0-2262-4b3b-ab35-cad4b44e967e	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	CET	Dendrimers are:	Linear polymers	Highly branched, tree-like nanoscale macromolecules	Carbon allotropes	Inorganic nanoparticles	B	Dendrimers are highly branched, tree-like (Greek: dendron = tree) synthetic macromolecules with a central core, branching layers (generations), and functional end groups. Size is precisely controlled (typically 1-10 nm). Used in drug delivery, gene therapy, MRI contrast agents, and catalysis. Monodisperse unlike conventional polymers.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
c0d674f6-5508-49f1-b625-39832835b988	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	ABOVE_CET	The Principle of Atom Economy was introduced by:	Paul Anastas	Barry Trost	Roger Sheldon	Peter Seeberger	B	Atom economy was introduced by Barry Trost (Stanford) in 1991 — one of the most influential concepts in green chemistry. He received the Presidential Green Chemistry Challenge Award for this concept. Atom economy = (MW of desired product / sum of MW of all reactants) x 100. He also introduced the concept of step economy.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
f5604e0e-7208-424a-b3bb-a2aafef14f2e	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	ABOVE_CET	In the synthesis of ibuprofen, the green BHC process has much higher atom economy than the classical Boots process because:	It uses more steps	It uses catalytic reactions replacing stoichiometric reagents, producing fewer byproducts	It uses more solvents	It operates at higher temperature	B	Classical Boots process (6 steps, atom economy ~40%): uses stoichiometric reagents, produces large amounts of salt waste. BHC (Boots-Hoechst-Celanese) green process (3 steps, atom economy ~77%): uses catalytic hydrogenation and carbonylation. Won Presidential Green Chemistry Award 1997. Classic example of green chemistry improving industrial synthesis.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
1d651550-e216-41dd-84b3-98062e7be343	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	ABOVE_CET	Quantum confinement in nanoparticles occurs when:	Particle size exceeds the Bohr exciton radius	Particle size is smaller than or comparable to the Bohr exciton radius	Temperature exceeds 1000 K	Surface area to volume ratio decreases	B	Quantum confinement occurs when nanoparticle size < Bohr exciton radius of the material. Electrons are spatially confined → discrete energy levels (vs continuous bands in bulk). This causes size-dependent bandgap: smaller particle = larger bandgap = blue-shifted emission. Explains size-tunable fluorescence of quantum dots.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
2b9c6868-c908-486b-9670-983a30c245ac	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	ABOVE_CET	The localized surface plasmon resonance (LSPR) of gold nanoparticles can be tuned by:	Changing the chemical formula of gold	Varying particle size, shape, and surrounding medium	Applying magnetic field	Changing temperature only	B	LSPR of AuNPs depends on: (1) particle size — larger particles redshift resonance, (2) particle shape — nanorods have two plasmon peaks (transverse + longitudinal), (3) dielectric constant of medium. Nanorods have NIR absorption (useful for photothermal cancer therapy). This tunability enables diverse optical applications.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
2bed0de7-3256-4f82-b4c0-2a6621a65443	a1111111-1111-1111-1111-111111111111	a153634f-5071-410f-b334-757b2746d58c	CET	When a wave reflects from a fixed (rigid) boundary, the phase change in the reflected wave is:	No phase change	pi/2 (90 degrees)	pi (180 degrees)	2*pi (360 degrees)	C	Reflection from a rigid (fixed, denser) boundary causes a phase change of pi (180 degrees). This is why a crest reflects as a trough. Free boundary causes no phase change.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 11:51:50.387703	1	1
94d857ce-2bce-48a9-9854-f84819cea210	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	ABOVE_CET	In ATRP (Atom Transfer Radical Polymerization), the control is achieved by:	Using excess initiator	Reversible deactivation of radicals by metal halide catalyst (Cu/Ru)	High temperature termination	Using only one type of monomer	B	ATRP is a controlled radical polymerization: transition metal catalyst (Cu(I)/Cu(II)) reversibly deactivates growing radicals via halogen atom transfer (KATO equilibrium). Low steady-state radical concentration minimizes termination. Gives narrow PDI (~1.1), controlled MW, and ability to make block copolymers. Green advantage: controlled synthesis reduces waste.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
ec1b2863-7147-4a12-9ae0-c0abf9555ea4	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	ABOVE_CET	The Meisenheimer complex is relevant to nucleophilic aromatic substitution. In green chemistry context, which mechanism gives better atom economy for aromatic substitution?	SNAr with electron-withdrawing groups on ring	Transition metal-catalyzed C-H activation (direct functionalization)	Classical electrophilic aromatic substitution with Lewis acid	Radical aromatic substitution	B	Transition metal-catalyzed C-H activation directly functionalizes C-H bonds without pre-halogenation — fewer steps, no halogenated waste, better atom economy. Classical EAS requires halogenated substrate + Lewis acid → metal halide waste. C-H activation represents ideal green chemistry: use C-H as functional handle directly.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
f1fbdaca-dcec-4ecd-9012-3cb49ceea233	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	ABOVE_CET	The Presidential Green Chemistry Challenge Awards are given by:	WHO	US EPA (Environmental Protection Agency)	IUPAC	Nobel Committee	B	The Presidential Green Chemistry Challenge Awards are given annually by the US EPA since 1996. They recognize industrial and academic achievements in green chemistry. Notable winners: BHC ibuprofen process, CO2 as solvent (SC Fluids), biocatalytic synthesis, and development of biodegradable polymers.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
7873657d-2ebd-4ea1-bd23-82583f23d557	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	ABOVE_CET	Single-walled carbon nanotubes (SWCNTs) can be metallic or semiconducting depending on:	Their length	Their chirality (rolling vector)	The temperature of synthesis	The carbon source used	B	SWCNT electronic properties depend on chirality — defined by chiral vector (n,m). If n-m is divisible by 3: metallic (conductivity like copper). Otherwise: semiconducting (bandgap ~0.5-1.5 eV). Armchair nanotubes (n=m) are always metallic. This has implications for nanotechnology applications in electronics.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
f9b2306d-0479-4992-a136-7cfd3074e5fd	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	ABOVE_CET	Life Cycle Assessment (LCA) in green chemistry evaluates:	Only the synthesis step of a chemical	Environmental impact from raw material extraction through disposal (cradle to grave)	Only the toxicity of final product	Economic cost of production	B	LCA evaluates environmental impact across entire product life cycle: raw material extraction → manufacturing → use → disposal (cradle to grave) or recycling (cradle to cradle). Considers energy use, water use, emissions, and waste at each stage. Essential tool for comparing greenness of different processes/products holistically.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
76ba1341-1d05-4527-b70a-c31138cc3c6e	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	ABOVE_CET	The preparation of nanoparticles by the citrate reduction method (Turkevich method) for gold nanoparticles uses:	NaBH4 as reducing agent	Sodium citrate as both reducing and stabilizing agent	Hydrazine as reducing agent	Ascorbic acid only as stabilizer	B	Turkevich method (1951): HAuCl4 reduced by sodium citrate at 100 deg C. Citrate acts as both reducing agent (reduces Au3+ to Au0) and capping/stabilizing agent (negatively charged citrate ions adsorb on AuNP surface preventing aggregation). Gives ~15-20 nm spherical AuNPs. Simple, reproducible, green synthesis.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
96692796-03ba-4ca6-bee9-09c10b848d21	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	ABOVE_CET	Biocatalysis is preferred in green chemistry because enzymes:	Work only at high temperatures	Are highly selective, work in water, and are biodegradable	Require organic solvents	Cannot be reused	B	Enzymes (biocatalysts) offer green advantages: (1) high chemo-, regio-, and stereo-selectivity → fewer byproducts, (2) operate in water at mild pH and temperature, (3) biodegradable, (4) can be immobilized for reuse. Used industrially: lipases for biodiesel, proteases in detergents, and whole-cell fermentation for pharmaceutical intermediates.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
304e040b-0d95-47c3-8686-4121ee9605b9	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	ABOVE_CET	The Stober process is used to synthesize:	Gold nanoparticles	Monodisperse silica nanoparticles	Carbon quantum dots	Iron oxide nanoparticles	B	Stober process (1968): hydrolysis and condensation of tetraethyl orthosilicate (TEOS) in ethanol/water/ammonia. Gives monodisperse silica (SiO2) nanoparticles (50 nm - 2 micrometers). Particle size controlled by TEOS/ammonia ratio. Used in cosmetics, chromatography supports, and drug delivery. Classic sol-gel synthesis.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
86b8cde9-f29a-4d31-bfe1-0aef7b8c73a2	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	ABOVE_CET	In the context of green metrics, PMI (Process Mass Intensity) is defined as:	Mass of product / Mass of all materials used	Total mass of all materials used / Mass of product	Mass of waste / Mass of solvent	Mass of catalyst / Mass of product	B	PMI = Total mass of all materials (reactants + solvents + water + catalysts) / Mass of desired product. Lower PMI = greener process. PMI = 1 is ideal (100% atom economy, no solvent). PMI incorporates solvent use (often dominant waste). Developed by ACS GCI Pharmaceutical Roundtable as comprehensive green metric.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
cda88c6f-b48f-41a8-bfaa-09f91e1c3269	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	ABOVE_CET	Superparamagnetic iron oxide nanoparticles (SPIONs) are used in medicine for:	Antimicrobial therapy only	MRI contrast enhancement and targeted drug delivery	Gene sequencing	Protein crystallization	B	SPIONs (Fe3O4 or gamma-Fe2O3, ~5-20 nm) show superparamagnetism — no remnant magnetization without field. Biomedical uses: (1) MRI contrast agents (T2 contrast), (2) targeted drug delivery (magnetic guidance), (3) hyperthermia cancer treatment (AC magnetic field heating), (4) cell labeling and separation. FDA-approved SPIONs exist for clinical use.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
18889bb8-2e9a-48e5-a5f1-26c59485544c	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	2a312e24-6628-4311-a6d6-4a90e8c515de	ABOVE_CET	The concept of "designing inherently safer chemicals" (Principle 4 of Green Chemistry) involves:	Making chemicals more reactive	Designing molecules with reduced toxicity while maintaining function	Avoiding all chemical synthesis	Using only natural chemicals	B	Principle 4: Design chemical products to be fully effective yet have little or no toxicity. Strategy: understand structure-activity relationships (SAR), avoid toxic functional groups, design for reduced bioaccumulation and persistence. Example: replacing chlorinated solvents with bio-based alternatives; designing biodegradable pesticides that degrade after use.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 03:04:52.728864	1	1
