acce13d4-6ea2-4359-a608-464ac2327417	a1111111-1111-1111-1111-111111111111	a153634f-5071-410f-b334-757b2746d58c	CET	If a wire of length L vibrates in 3 segments, the wavelength of stationary wave is:	L/3	2L/3	3L	L	B	3 segments means 3 loops: L = 3*(lambda/2), so lambda = 2L/3.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 11:51:50.387703	1	1
0e3ead1a-d54c-4e23-bcd9-1ad12c15bee9	a1111111-1111-1111-1111-111111111111	a153634f-5071-410f-b334-757b2746d58c	ABOVE_CET	Two waves y1 = 4*sin(wt + pi/3) and y2 = 4*sin(wt - pi/3) cm superpose. The resultant amplitude is:	8 cm	4 cm	4*sqrt(3) cm	4*sqrt(2) cm	B	Phase difference = 2*pi/3. Resultant amp = 2A*cos(delta/2) = 2*4*cos(pi/3) = 8*(1/2) = 4 cm.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 11:51:50.387703	1	1
12616bd3-8850-48bb-8fda-554ef1f65903	a1111111-1111-1111-1111-111111111111	a153634f-5071-410f-b334-757b2746d58c	ABOVE_CET	A string of length 1 m and mass 0.01 kg is stretched with tension 100 N. The fundamental frequency is:	50 Hz	100 Hz	200 Hz	25 Hz	A	m = 0.01/1 = 0.01 kg/m. v = sqrt(T/m) = sqrt(100/0.01) = sqrt(10000) = 100 m/s. f = v/(2L) = 100/2 = 50 Hz.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-05 11:51:50.387703	1	1
