2f24d105-3767-4fc3-b3e2-9833d6db9eb3	a1111111-1111-1111-1111-111111111111	f1110007-0000-0000-0000-000000000007	CET	Total internal reflection occurs when light travels from:	Rarer to denser medium at any angle	Denser to rarer medium beyond critical angle	Rarer to denser medium beyond critical angle	Denser to rarer medium at any angle	B	Total internal reflection (TIR) has two conditions: (1) light must travel from optically denser to rarer medium, and (2) angle of incidence must exceed the critical angle. At critical angle, refracted ray grazes the surface (90 degrees). Beyond it, all light is reflected back into denser medium. TIR is used in optical fibers, periscopes, and diamond cutting to maximize brilliance.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-12 08:50:56.994423	1	1
9b05c310-68d3-4143-a7f5-866382255105	a1111111-1111-1111-1111-111111111111	f1110007-0000-0000-0000-000000000007	CET	A concave mirror has focal length 15 cm. An object is placed 10 cm in front of it. The nature of the image is:	Real, inverted, diminished	Virtual, erect, magnified	Real, inverted, magnified	Virtual, erect, diminished	B	Using mirror formula: 1/v + 1/u = 1/f. u = -10 cm, f = -15 cm (concave mirror). 1/v = 1/f - 1/u = 1/(-15) - 1/(-10) = -1/15 + 1/10 = (-2+3)/30 = 1/30. So v = +30 cm. Positive v means image is behind mirror — virtual and erect. Magnification m = -v/u = -30/(-10) = +3, so image is magnified. Object is between F and P, so image is virtual, erect, magnified.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-12 08:50:56.994423	1	1
4114450e-f594-401e-bcea-18330747225c	a1111111-1111-1111-1111-111111111111	f1110007-0000-0000-0000-000000000007	CET	The refractive index of glass is 1.5. The critical angle for glass-air interface is approximately:	30 degrees	42 degrees	48 degrees	60 degrees	B	Critical angle C is given by sin C = 1/mu = 1/1.5 = 0.667. So C = sin^-1(0.667) approximately 41.8 degrees approximately 42 degrees. Beyond this angle, total internal reflection occurs. The critical angle depends only on the refractive indices of the two media. Higher refractive index means smaller critical angle — diamonds have very small critical angle (~24 degrees), causing brilliant sparkle.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-12 08:50:56.994423	1	1
d9fd3fe5-90a9-4194-9065-deacc78bed8c	a1111111-1111-1111-1111-111111111111	f1110007-0000-0000-0000-000000000007	CET	A ray of light passes from air into water (refractive index 1.33) at an angle of incidence of 30 degrees. The angle of refraction is approximately:	22 degrees	30 degrees	40 degrees	45 degrees	A	Using Snell's law: n1 sin(i) = n2 sin(r). 1 x sin(30) = 1.33 x sin(r). sin(r) = sin(30)/1.33 = 0.5/1.33 = 0.376. r = sin^-1(0.376) approximately 22 degrees. The ray bends toward the normal when entering a denser medium (water). The angle of refraction (22 degrees) is less than angle of incidence (30 degrees), consistent with going from rarer to denser medium.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-12 08:50:56.994423	1	1
