df648436-7f67-46b7-9f9c-f7f04a31fa02	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	13aa8290-9ee6-433e-b1a7-5521641fa088	ABOVE_CET	The standard electrode potential of Li is -3.05 V, more negative than Cs (-2.92 V), even though Li has a higher ionization enthalpy. The main reason is:	Li has lower atomic mass	Li^+ has very high hydration enthalpy due to its small size	Li forms more stable compounds	Li has a larger atomic radius than Cs	B	The electrode potential depends on three energy factors: sublimation enthalpy, ionization enthalpy, and hydration enthalpy. Although Li has higher IE, its extremely small Li^+ ion has a very high hydration enthalpy (about -519 kJ/mol vs -264 for Cs+). The large hydration energy more than compensates, making Li^+/Li the most negative electrode potential.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-12 10:01:16.564709	1	1
579c1151-30e6-4499-b18c-e5f796c45196	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	13aa8290-9ee6-433e-b1a7-5521641fa088	ABOVE_CET	When Na2O2 reacts with water, the products are:	NaOH only	NaOH and O2	NaOH and H2O2	Na2O and O2	C	2Na2O2 + 2H2O -> 4NaOH + O2. However, the intermediate product is H2O2: Na2O2 + H2O -> 2NaOH + H2O2, which then decomposes: 2H2O2 -> 2H2O + O2. In cold water, H2O2 can be isolated as an intermediate. Both NaOH and H2O2 are formed initially.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-12 10:01:16.564709	1	1
ad50f0b3-f770-4288-86a5-866e322a2636	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	13aa8290-9ee6-433e-b1a7-5521641fa088	ABOVE_CET	The anomalous behaviour of Be is similar to Al (diagonal relationship). Which of the following properties is NOT shared by Be and Al?	Both form amphoteric oxides	Both form covalent halides	Both react with dilute HNO3 to give the same products	Both are rendered passive by concentrated HNO3	C	Be and Al share: amphoteric oxides (react with acids and bases), covalent halides (BeCl2, AlCl3 are covalent), passivation by conc. HNO3. However, their reactions with dilute HNO3 are not identical — Al does react with dilute HNO3 but the products differ. The diagonal relationship covers structural/bonding similarities, not all chemical reactions.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-12 10:01:16.564709	1	1
