41c2dcfa-0c06-41a4-9c1f-29a35a056d37	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	13aa8290-9ee6-433e-b1a7-5521641fa088	ABOVE_CET	The white precipitate that forms when CO2 is passed into limewater, and then dissolves on passing excess CO2, finally re-precipitates on boiling. The final precipitate is:	Ca(OH)2	CaCO3	Ca(HCO3)2	CaO	B	On boiling Ca(HCO3)2 solution: Ca(HCO3)2 -> CaCO3 (ppt) + H2O + CO2. CaCO3 re-precipitates because CO2 is expelled by heating, shifting the equilibrium back. This is the basis of lime kiln chemistry and cave formation reversal.	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-12 10:01:16.564709	1	1
dfb4cf97-ecb8-4352-9610-7225e3814f6b	b2222222-2222-2222-2222-222222222222	13aa8290-9ee6-433e-b1a7-5521641fa088	ABOVE_CET	The n-factor of Na2O2 when it reacts with water (acting as an oxidising agent where O goes from -1 to -2) is:	1	2	0.5	4	A	In Na2O2: O is -1. In the reaction with water to give NaOH: O^2- = -2 (one O is reduced from -1 to -2). The other O is released as O2 (0) — oxidised from -1 to 0. Per formula unit of Na2O2: 1 electron is gained and 1 is lost. For the oxidising half: n-factor = 1 (1 electron gained per Na2O2 for the reduction half).	60	f	\N	t	2026-06-12 10:01:16.564709	1	1
